This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.AI because it deals with argumentation problems, which are often studied in the field of artificial intelligence. The implementation of a ranking-based semantics also involves computational methods, which further supports the classification of this paper under cs.AI. 

The paper may also belong to the sub-category of cs.LG, as it involves the use of machine learning techniques to rank arguments based on preference relations. 

The sub-category of cs.DS is also a possibility, as the implementation of a ranking-based semantics involves the manipulation and analysis of data structures representing abstract argumentation frameworks. 

The paper may also be classified under cs.GT, as it involves the application of computational social choice methods to argumentation framework ranking-based semantics. 

Finally, the sub-category of cs.CL is a possibility, as the paper deals with natural language processing and the analysis of arguments expressed in natural language.
